{
  "body" : "Create a minimalist ultra-high-resolution travel poster in line-art style for {{city_name}}, portraying the city as a stylish everyday urban scene rather than a tourist postcard.\n\n— Main composition —\nCentral composition features {{city_name}}'s most iconic everyday street scene:\n{{scene_focus}}\nLandmarks should blend subtly into daily life rather than dominate the composition. The image should feel like a *resident's* view of the city, not a tourist's.\n\n— Foreground people —\n{{people_archetypes}}\nPeople naturally reflect local street fashion, lifestyle, and modern urban culture. They are drawn at the same line weight and density as the architecture — they belong to the city, not pasted on top of it.\n\n— Background detail —\nBackground filled with authentic local signage, cafés, restaurants, convenience stores, transport signs, storefronts, vending machines, awnings, electrical cables, traffic lights, mailboxes, and architectural details. Use authentic, culturally-recognizable typography on the signs (real-language characters, not gibberish glyphs).\n\n— Typography & text quality (EXTREMELY IMPORTANT) —\nLarge centered title at the top: \"{{city_name}}\" — set in a clean, geometric, slightly condensed sans-serif (think Akzidenz-Grotesk / Neue Haas Grotesk / Helvetica Now Display), all caps, with generous letter-spacing.\nSubtitle at the bottom: \"{{subtitle_native}}\" — smaller, in a culturally appropriate typeface (Japanese: Hiragino Sans / Yu Gothic; Chinese: 思源黑体 / 苹方; Korean: Pretendard; Arabic: Naskh; Latin: matching the title).\nAll typography must be clean, readable, professionally designed. Japanese / Chinese / Korean / Arabic signage in the background must appear authentic and natural — NO random symbols, NO broken or distorted letters, NO gibberish glyphs that look like real characters but aren't.\n\n— Style —\nUltra-clean vector illustration. Swiss modernist travel poster aesthetic. Monoline line-art. Mid-century editorial illustration. Architectural illustration with crisp geometric perspective. Japanese graphic poster design discipline (think Kazumasa Nagai, Kenya Hara, Ikko Tanaka). Premium travel-brand aesthetic in the spirit of Acne Studios travel guides, MUJI city series, and Monocle magazine illustrations.\n\n— Line style —\nMonochrome line illustration only. Thin, highly precise lines, predominantly uniform stroke weight (true monoline). Minimal fill areas — almost everything is described by line, with at most 5–10% solid-fill accents (e.g., one lit window, one dark awning) for visual rhythm.\n{{line_density}}. Rhythmic arrangement of signs, buildings, windows, cables, and street objects. Visually dense yet highly organized composition — every element is intentional, no random clutter.\n\n— Color system (VERY IMPORTANT) —\nUse ONLY ONE primary ink color: {{ink_color}}, on ONE background color: {{background_color}}. NO additional colors. NO rainbow palettes. NO neon glow effects. NO gradients within the line color.\nMonochrome silkscreen / risograph poster aesthetic — the entire image must be reproducible as a single-color screen print on tinted paper.\n\n— Composition & framing —\n{{aspect_ratio}}, vertical poster layout. {{perspective}}. Pedestrians naturally crossing streets and moving through the scene with believable trajectories. Balanced urban rhythm and visual flow — eye should travel naturally from title → main intersection → secondary detail → subtitle.\n\n— Mood —\nStylish urban life, calm yet lively atmosphere, high-end travel magazine cover aesthetic, timeless city identity, premium tourism campaign visuals, minimalist yet highly detailed.\n\n— Additional details —\n{{extra_notes}}\n\n— Strictly avoid —\n- Do NOT use more than ONE ink color besides the background\n- Do NOT add gradients, glow, drop shadows, or neon effects to the lines\n- Do NOT generate gibberish characters in CJK / Arabic signage — if uncertain, use abstract bars instead of fake characters\n- Do NOT make landmarks dominate (no giant tower in the center) — keep the city skyline implicit and integrated\n- Do NOT crowd the title area — keep clear breathing space around \"{{city_name}}\" and \"{{subtitle_native}}\"\n- Do NOT use comic / cartoon proportions for people — they must match the architectural line discipline\n- Do NOT add photographic textures, watercolor washes, or brushy strokes — pure clean vector lines only\n- Do NOT add any logo, watermark, signature, frame border, or stock-illustration trademark\n- Do NOT use random latin filler text (no \"Lorem Ipsum\", no decorative \"PREMIUM\" stamps)\n\n— Output —\nVertical poster composition. Ultra-detailed 8K resolution. Print-ready. Ultra-precise vector-quality rendering. Should look indistinguishable from a hand-drawn editorial illustration that was vectorized for print.\n\nKeywords: travel poster, line-art, monoline, Swiss modernist, monochrome silkscreen, city poster, editorial illustration, vector, mid-century, Japanese graphic design, premium travel brand, {{city_name}}",
